description.value:
Terracotta figure of dwarf with basket of food.
A somewhat grotesque male celebrant, rather dwarfish, corpulent and bandy-legged: a hole for his gigantic lost inserted phallus forces his knees apart; his navel protrudes and he has receding hair. He is largely naked, with a himation rolled up and encircling his waist, the two ends hanging down on each of his thighs. A garland hangs round his neck and rests on his chest, and he wears a conical hat with a knob at the top, tied with ribbon round the brim, the knot on the front. His left hand supports a basket on his shoulder, the basket holding two round fruits and three bunches of grapes, with vine-leaves between them. His lowered right hand holds a small furry animal by its rear legs; it has a short tail, and may be a dog or pig. There is minimal detail at the rear and a suspension-lug is placed behind the neck (the feet are flat below and there is no plinth).

description.value:
Fragmentary black granite group figure with separate cast of original heads, much of the left side and base now lost.

At the top of the granite fragment the ends of two separate wigs are visible, with the right side figure wearing a longer wig than the left side figure. Traces of another raised ridge at the left side may indicate that a third figure was originally part of the composition. Beneath the ends of the wigs are the name of Ramses II in a cartouche and queen Nefertari with a rectangular border. Directly underneath their names are the upper parts of four columns of text. Along the curved right shoulder are the remains of three horizontal lines of incised text reading from the front towards the reverse of the figure. There are also traces of yellow paint within some of these signs.

description.value: Limestone statuette of a Kourotrophos, possibly Isis with Horus, painted. Isis and Horus; a woman is sitting on a throne with square-cut sides, her feet resting on a footstool. She is wearing a garment with a kolpos below the knees and a veil which is loosely placed on her head and is reaching down to the arm-rest. Her hair is falling on the shoulders, and is not covering her large ears. She is wearing a necklace with a pendant, which lies between her sturdy and high breasts. Her face is round. On her lap she is holding a small, long, nude boy who is rendered flatly. His legs are closed and are lying to the left, his head is resting at the woman's left breats. Both of his slim arms are embracing the upper body of the mother. The back is flat. Her left cheek and some corners of the throne are missing. Traces of red paint on inside of veil, collar and necklace.

description.value: Light grey limestone head from a kouros, painted.  Head from a large statuette, broken from chin to approximately the ear-level of the back of the head. The tip of the nose is missing. Behind the right ear is a perforation.  The face is narrow and tapering towards a pointed chin; the back of the head is flat and continues straight as the surviving part shows. The cheeks are fleeing towards the back. The surface is treated in a fine manner, convex and concave lines are merging. The eyes are slightly downcast; the slightly protruding, oval eyes are framed by fine eyelids. The right eye is oblique, the left straight; the eyebrows are indicated by protruding bands. The nose is long, the tip, now broken off, was thicker. The mouth is small, the thin lips slightly curved, the edges turned up to a light smile; the lower lip and the small pointy chin recoil slightly. The ears are very large with swollen lobes. The nose is large, the mouth small and slightly bowed. Across the forehead, from ear to ear, is a thick diadem or hairband which is covered by some locks around the temples; the perforation behind the ear might have served for the attachment of some kind of decoration for the hair. The forelocks are centrally parted and are falling in five sharply separated tresses behind the ears and down to the neck, seven tresses are falling down from the lower centre of the head.   There are traces of black paint on the hair and the right eye, traces of red remain on the lips and the hairband.

description.value:
Black basalt base for a seated figure, the feet intact on top of the base.

Across the top of the base is a semi-circular fragment of the wide throne or seat, with a small square recess in the centre. This was likely used to attach the figure or a separately made portion of the seat. The surviving feet are broken from the ankle, and are positioned close together. On the reverse is a small circular hole on the seat where it meets the top of the base. Neither the top or sides of the base bear any surviving trace of inscription.

The left corner of the base has broken off, and there are small chips and scratches around all edges of the base.

description.value: Plaster face of Tutankhamun or his Queen: this face was cast from a single mold. Its rounded edges and uneven, lumpy back surface are typical results of a process in which liquid plaster is poured into an open mold. The face is symmetrical in structure and presents stylized forms. The surface texture of the cast is noticeably gritty and pitted. Stylistically, there is a restrained sensitivity and sweetly melancholic expression of the youthful face. It has a wing-shaped mouth, small chin, and slanted eyes below sharply accentuated brows.

description.value:
Fragmentary green steatite male figure, broken from the torso.

He wears a shoulder-length wavy wig, with an undersection of tight curls around the ends of the wig and below both ears. His eyebrows are thick and arched, and his eyes are narrow with a heavy upper eyelid. The mouth and nose are damaged but the outline of the left side is intact. His face is fleshy at the jawline. His upper body is bare, with a cartouche of Amenhotep III on the right breast and another partial cartouche on the right upper arm. On the reverse is the top section of a slim back-pillar, inscribed with finely incised text.

The surface of the chest and shoulders are heavily chipped and scratched, and part of the right side of the head and face is now missing. The object is attached to a modern wooden base.

description.value:
Fragmentary black granite female figure.

She wears a heavy Hathor wig with plaited detail on the reverse. Her hair is tucked behind the oversized ears, and the top left side of her wig has been damaged. Her eyes are elongated and flat, with a thin line conveying the brows. Her nose is short and flat, and her lips are thick and pursed. Around her neck she wears a simple broad-collar. From the shoulders the body has been re-shaped and rounded, though traces of a single line from her shoulder may indicate her clothing. The lower surface of the figure has been smoothed and likely seems designed to be used as a tool known as a pounder. These were part of a collection of stone tools often used when working with harder stones such as granite.

description.value:
Head of a green basalt male figure, broken from the neck.

He has a shaven head with subtle modelling of the skull. His ears are oversized and simplistically formed, and appear to be pinned far back from the face. His eyes are extremely narrow with a heavy upper eyelid, and a faint arched ridge above indicating the eyebrows. His nose is broad at the tip, with a deep line on either side of the nose conveying a small fold of flesh. His lips are pursed together and the outer corners of the mouth are flat. His cheeks and jawline are fleshy, and the chin appears to be raised creating the suggestion of an upward gaze.

There are numerous small chips across the head and face. The object is now attached to a small modern base.

description.value: Limestone seated figure of the goddess Isis on a low backed chair, suckling Horus-the-Child (Harpocrates).   The goddess is depicted wearing a tight-fitting sheath dress that reaches to the ankles, and a modius crown topped with the sun-disc and horns. She wears a long and smooth wig tucked behind the ears, with the raised hood and head of the uraeus cobra placed above her forehead. Her eyes are wide and almond shaped, with thick eyebrows that slope downwards to meet the elongated cosmetic lines that are depicted along her outer eye. The face is extremely fleshy and rounded, particularly around the jawline and neck. Lower portion of a naophorous schist figure of Sety, shown kneeling with an image of the god Ptah.

He wears a long pleated garment with a thick belt across his waist, and a single strap of material extending over his right side. The same detail is found partly intact on his left side. He is shown kneeling and resting on his heels. On his right side the outline of his forearm is intact, and indicates that his arm extended out to hold onto the naos shrine placed between his knees. Lower portion of a naophorous schist figure of Sety, shown kneeling with an image of the god Ptah.

He wears a long pleated garment with a thick belt across his waist, and a single strap of material extending over his right side. The same detail is found partly intact on his left side. He is shown kneeling and resting on his heels. On his right side the outline of his forearm is intact, and indicates that his arm extended out to hold onto the naos shrine placed between his knees. The surviving front section of the naos shrine includes the lower legs and feet of the god Ptah, shown in mummified form and holding a was sceptre. description.value: White limestone female figure, standing and wearing a dress with central bundle of vertical folds; fragmentary. The head is missing. Scratches running obliquely across the upper body, apart from that hardly any damages. Part broken off on right shoulder and right wrist.The woman with her broad shoulders is wearing a garment which is tightly fitted to the small waist and the sturdy breasts. The arms are not closely attached to the body but are connected with it by means of small baulks.The left arm hangs down straight, the right is held at a 90 degree angle in front of the belly grasping the strongly protruding bundle of folds which falls down vertically from the centre of the belly between the feet. The skirt is billowing out a little towards the bottom and swings in a light curve. The naked feet stand slightly straddled on the plinth which is almost rectangular with a rounded frontal area. Seen in profile the belly is strongly protruding. The back is neglected, the arms are a little removed from the rounded body.

description.value: Limestone statue of a male official shown seated on a backless chair.  The figure is depicted in a seated position with the legs and feet set slightly apart and both hands placed across the lap, with the left palm held flat against the knee while the right hand fist is clenched. He wears a knee-length kilt and a short curled wig, which is set high on the forehead and obscures the ears. The upper body bare, with modelling of the extremely narrowed waist and broad shoulders. The arms and lower legs are comparatively wider than the rest of the body, creating an overall disproportionate shape. The eyes are narrow and slightly slanted, with thin arched eyebrows. The nose is extremely short while the mouth is wide with thick lips which are both sharply incised. description.value: The upper part of a hollow terracotta grotesque cult-attendant carrying a statue of Amun-Min (Pan) in procession; the bearer is naked but wears a knobbed conical hat. He swings a reel-shaped object on a thong in his right hand, an incense-diffuser or a bullroarer. The statue is carried on his left shoulder, held by its ankles, and is shown seated. It differs in this, and in its nakedness, from the Pharaonic Min, who normally stands, and is wrapped as a mummy; it does, however, wear the Amun crown with feathers and holds its right arm up in the standard manner; its left hand is placed close to, but does not grip, its large phallus, and it wears a garland round the neck. The back of the group is largely unmodelled, but the buttocks of the theophoros are indicated well. There is a circular depression for the placement of a vent. Two-piece mould. Micaceous brown Nile silt. Traces of a white dressing, mostly on the front.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta figure of Isis anasyr(o)mene. A figure of ‘Isis-Aphrodite anasyr(o)mene’, perhaps Isis-Bubastis, holding the front of her tunic up to show her pubic area; the back of the garment falls in curved folds of drapery beside her legs. She stands on a small, round-fronted, inadequate plinth. Her hair is parted in the middle and Isis-locks fall onto her shoulders; she wears a huge, closely woven double-wreath bound across the front with a narrow horizontal garland tied at each side; leaves fall beside her upper arms, below these leaves hang wide ribbons from the headdress. From the top of the wreath rises a large flaring kalathos, surviving to its full height only at the back. The back is plain. The front is covered with a white dressing and the flesh is left in this colour, except for the right forearm, which appears to be painted red. The dress is painted pink, as is the lowermost element of the double-wreath: the upper part is painted yellow. The horizontal garland is painted blue and its ribbon ties are red. Also painted blue are the leaves hanging from the wreath. The plinth is coloured red. Hollow, from two-piece mould. Brown Nile silt, with abundant fine gold mica, quartz and white inclusions.

description.value: Granodiorite figure of an official: the man sits with both arms extended on his lap. He wears a long robe tied above his waist, which is a typical type of dress for an official of his day; the knot with which it is tied is clearly visible. He wears a smooth shoulder length hairstyle or wig with pointed lappets. The proper left-hand side of the statue is uninscribed, while the proper right bears an offering formula to Osiris. The texts on the statue are very worn and difficult to read. There are two further texts on the front and base of the seat, either side of the figure, also offering formulas, one to Osiris, lord of Ankhtawy (Memphis) and the other to Ptah-Sokar; it is quite likely that these are to be understood as formulas to the same necropolis deity, the composite Ptah-Sokar-Osiris. The name of the owner is not clearly preserved, but appears to be Iwy or lay; the name of his mother is uncertain. His title appears to be that of "bowman."

description.value: Granodiorite seated statue of a male official.   He wears a smooth shoulder-length wig with sharp pointed ends, set high on the forehead and tucked behind the oversized ears. His eyes are wide and almond shaped, with a heavy upper eyelid and deep-set eyebrows. The nose is long and slim, and the mouth is small in size. There appears to be a subtle fold of flesh on either side of the mouth, and the face is rounded at the jawline. He sits on a low-backed chair and wears a long kilt which is tied via a knot at the waist. His upper body is bare, and his arms are held by his sides with the palms placed flat on the outer edge of each thigh. The right side of the seat includes an inscription, and further text is also inscribed across the front of the seat on either side of the figure’s legs, and at the top of the statue base beside his feet. description.value: Fragmentary steatite amuletic figure of the goddess Isis with the lower body now missing, originally representing Isis suckling Horus-the-Child (Harpocrates) seated on his mother’s lap.  Isis is depicted wearing a modius crown topped with the sun-disc and horns, with the uraeus placed against the forehead. She also wears a sheath dress and long striated wig, set low on the forehead and tucked behind the ears. Her eyes are wide and almond shaped, with thick eyebrows that slope downwards to meet the elongated cosmetic lines that are depicted at her outer eye. The nose and mouth are broad, with the outer corners of the mouth upturned to suggest a small smile. The face is fleshy and rounded particularly around the jawline and neck. Her arms are held close to the body with the right hand placed over the left breast, and the positioning of the left arm likely a modern restoration. description.value: Fragmentary steatite head and upper body of a young male figure, the lower body and base now lost.  The figure is depicted wearing a long braided wig with horizontal striations, set low on the forehead and with the plaited braid falling onto the figure’s back. His large ears protruding slightly forwards. The upper body appears to be bare and there is a notable swelling of the muscle at the chest and a narrowing of the waist. The eyes are wide and with a heavy ridge depicting the upper eyelid, the left side eye now slightly faded. The nose is long and broad at the tip, and the mouth is full with thick lips which are slightly asymmetrical in shape. The face is particularly rounded and fleshy in appearance at the jawline and neck.   There are a number of small chips across the statue surface, with slightly larger chips to the right side ear, top of the wig, and damage to the bridge of the nose. The figure is attached to a modern rectangular base.

description.value: Fragmentary steatite head of a male figure.   He wears a smooth rounded wig which is set high on the forehead and obscures the ears. His eyes are narrow with a heavy ridge indicating the upper eyelids. A faint sloping ridge conveys the eyebrows. His nose is broad at the nostrils, and his upper lip is thick and fleshy. The lower lip is thin and sharply incised. The outer corners of the mouth are flat, and his face appears rounded and fleshy around the mouth and chin.  The right side of the face below the eye and at the chin below the lower lip are both chipped. There are further chips around the edge of the wig at the forehead, and several small scratches across the wig at the front and both sides. The figure is now attached to a modern rectangular base.

description.value:
Limestone figure of Osiris seated on a high backed throne.

Osiris wears the atef-crown, false-beard, and holds a was sceptre at his chest that extends down to his feet. His eyes are rounded with a thick ridge indicating the upper eyelid, and his nose is slim with the right side now partly damaged. His lips are thick and pursed together. His head is tilted upwards. His body is mummified. At his feet are the remains of a paper label, now illegible. Across the top of the base is a single line of hieroglyphic text with some of the god's epithets. The throne may once have been round-topped, however the tip of this is now lost.

There are numerous gouges to the stone at the edges of the throne and corners of the base.

There are numerous gouges to the stone at the edges of the throne and corners of the base.

description.value:
Fragmentary grey stone head of the creator god Ptah.

The god typically wears a close-fitting cap crown which is not clearly delineated here, as the head is portrayed as smooth with no discernible areas to attach a headdress or crown. His eyes are almond shaped eyes and he has hollow, thin eyebrows that would have originally been inlaid with another material. The outline of his broad nose is visible on the left side of the face, and the mouth is small with thick lips pursed together. He wears a slim false beard at his chin.

A thin crack in the stone is visible across the centre of the face and extending over the top of the head and onto the reverse. Both ears are chipped around the edges and the nose and tip of the false beard have broken off. The object is now attached to a small modern base.

description.value:
Head from a limestone male figure, the body and base now missing.

The figure wears a short styled wig with individual tresses of the hair delineated from the centre of the head. His head is raised, creating the suggestion of an upward gaze. Black paint has been applied across the wig while red-brown paint has been used to denote his skin. His eyes are wide with slim lines of black paint around the eyelids, and the eyebrows are faint but slightly arched. The nose is slim and the mouth is small in size with the outer corners visibly upturned. On the reverse are the remains of the top of what was likely a back-pillar or seat, which also has traces of white paint.

There are small chips around the neck area and on both sides of the face, and on the reverse of the wig. The figure is attached to a small modern base.

description.value: A hollow terracotta female acrobat (its comparanda thought by others to be male), seated with knees pressed against her body, and supporting on upraised hands an object largely broken away, but having a lower horizontal moulding at the rear. She is naked except for briefs, marked with impressions (to represent an animal skin?), and has a necklace with three strung elements: two beads and a pendant. Her hair is cut short. Summary treatment at the back. Feet repaired in plaster, but now damaged: perhaps an ancient repair. The left knee is broken away. A hole has been bored underneath for a modern stand. Two-piece mould. The back design does not 'fit' the front, in that the rear of the head is enormous compared with the face, neither do the arms match nor does the rump. Micaceous red-brown Nile silt. Slight traces of an overall white dressing.

description.value: Terracotta seated youth.  A naked youth, modelled in the round and seated on a rectangular plinth, his legs extended before him, the knees slightly raised. From between his legs a colossal phallus curves up to rest its glans on the side of his head. Both his arms stretch out to hold the phallus, but his right hand is thrust inside a round-bottomed pot with a substantial rim. His face is turned to his right and his head is shaven except for a side-lock that hangs down his back.  Solid; two-piece mould.  Micaceous deep brown Nile silt with a coat of white dressing, much of which remains. The flesh is painted pink, except for the glans, which is coloured dark pink; the top of the plinth was painted bright blue, and the pot appears to have been black.

description.value:
Fragmentary upper body of a granite male figure.

He wears a smooth shoulder-length wig which is set low on the forehead. An undersection of tight curls are visible below the ears. His facial features are small while the lower half of the face is particularly broad. His eyes are narrow and slanted, with thick arched eyebrows that converge at the bridge of his slim nose. His lips are full and pursed together. Around his neck he wears a broad-collar with four rows of beaded detail, and at his shoulders are the pleated sleeves of his clothing. The chest is subtly defined while there is a suggestion of a narrowed waist. Both arms appear to have been held at the sides of the body. On the reverse is the upper portion of a slim back-pillar, which has no clear inscription.

There are numerous cracks extending across the upper body and small chips are visible on the wig and face. The object is now attached to a modern rectangular base.

description.value:
Fragmentary steatite figure of a nude child figure, the lower legs and base now lost.

The female figure wears a side-lock of hair on the right side, a visual indication of her youth. The ears and facial features are crudely carved, with the outer corners of her oversized eyes extending downwards. The nose and mouth are broad while the lips appear thin and sharply incised. The neck is extremely broad and there is little definition between the chin and neck area. She is portrayed nude, with small rounded breasts and a narrowed waist. There are incised lines outlining the genitalia and the upper thighs. The arms are held by the sides of the body. On the reverse is a slim back-pillar that reaches to the upper back, with notable damage across the surface that renders any possible inscription underneath illegible.

There are numerous chips and scratches to the stone surface, including chips to the top of the head and face. Long scratches are also visible across the chest… (See Merlin record for full description)

description.value:
Fragmentary limestone upper body of a male figure.

He wears an intricate double-wig with traces of black paint. His thick eyebrows are carved in raised relief, and he has a thick upper eyelid extending into a wide cosmetic line at the outer corners. His nose is long and slim, and he has thick lips with the outer corners of his mouth slightly upturned suggesting a slight smile. There are traces of a white substance across the lower left side of the face and neck. The upper body is damaged at the neck and chest, and there are no indications of clothing or jewellery. On the reverse are the remains of a slim back-pillar, and though damaged it appears to be uninscribed.

His head has been damaged at the top right side, above the forehead, and on the reverse. The tip of the nose has broken off and there are numerous chips to the rest of the stone surface, including gouges to the lower part of the back-pillar.

description.value:
Fragmentary steatite male figure, the lower body now lost.

He wears a short wig that is set far back from his forehead, with cross-hatched detail across the surface indicating curls. His forehead is large with visible frown lines. The eyebrows are thick and elongated, meeting at the nose area and extending out to the edges of the wig. The eyes are set extremely far apart and represented with two small rings of another material, possibly bone. The mouth is a small oval-shaped hole within the stone, and he wears a short beard with cross-hatched detail. Around his neck he wears a beaded necklace. The upper arms are broken off at the shoulder, and the upper portion of his chest features a deep vertical line down the centre of the stone. On the reverse his back is left flat and unformed.

There are a number of small scratches and abrasions to the stone surface. The object is now supported on a small modern base.

description.value:
Fragmentary limestone head of a male figure, only the front section of the head now remaining.

He wears a striated wig that has broken off at the ears. A faded red colour is visilbe on the left side. His eyebrows are arched and modelled in raised relief. His eyes are narrow, with a thick incised line around the lids and a cosmetic line at the outer corners. His nose is long and broad at the nostrils, with a clear cupid’s bow above the upper lip. The outer corners of his mouth are upturned to form a small smile. Small traces of a red-brown paint are visible on the lower ears and the jawline, likely used to convey the skin. At the chin is a small broken section of stone that possibly was once a beard.

There are numerous small cracks across the stone surface. The tip of the nose is missing and there is damage across the eyebrows and left eye. The object is now attached to a small modern base.

description.value:
Fragmentary limestone head of Osiris, the body and base now missing.

Osiris wears the tall feathered atef-crown with a raised outline of the uraeus cobra body across the front of the crown. His ears stick out from underneath the feathered edges. The eyes are slanted and narrow, with thick flat eyebrows set close to the eyes and a slim nose p. The mouth is small with sharply incised lips, and the outer corners pulled up high. Though damaged from the chin, it is likely that the god also wore a divine false beard. On the reverse is a large broad back-pillar, its round top reaching to the tip of the god’s crown. It does not appear to be inscribed.

A large chip to the centre of the crown is visible on the right side, and at the right side feather there is also another chip to the stone just above the ear. There are small chips to the stone around the edges of the ostrich feathers on either side. The figure is now attached to a small modern base.

description.value: Steatite statuette of a baboon representing the god Thoth.   The figure is depicted in a seated position on top of a tall pedestal, which is curved at the back and features a double flight of steps incised on the front. The baboon is shown with the front paws placed on the knees, and the tail curled around the right side hind leg. The ‘feathered hood’ or layers of fur of the chest are conveyed through detailed thin incisions. A bronze lunar disc has been attached to the head of the baboon.  The lunar disc is corroded, and the front edge of the pedestal is now broken. There are several small chips to the top of the head and face of the baboon. There are also several scratches to the sides of the pedestal and a chip at the end of the baboon’s tail, otherwise the figure is in good condition.

description.value:
Fragmentary burnt limestone figure of a seated female, the upper body now missing.

She wears a long dress which reaches to the ankles as indicated by the faint remaining outline of her clothing along the lower legs. Around the lower edges of the seat on both sides and at the front of the seat beside the lower legs of the figure are traces of a striped pattern, the upper part of each now lost. On the reverse the remains of the block throne include a separate section resembling a back-pillar, which does not appear to be inscribed.

In addition to the loss of the upper body of the figure, there is considerable damage to the seat and base of the figure including a large chip to the right side of the seat. The left side lower leg of the figure is also partially broken, and there are chips across the upper legs particularly along the right knee. The edges of the base are also badly damaged at the corners. The object has been attached to a tall rectangular modern base.

The most visible parts of the sculpture have been carefully finished and retain the original polish except on the cat’s chest and around his right front leg where scars from the claw chisel survive. Those areas that would have been partially concealed have been left in a coarser state.  The front part of the neck has been gouged out but has been concealed by a modern plaster fill.  Below this the cat’s chest is roughly worked and rather flat. The raised, right front leg has only been roughly blocked out on its left side and the cat and the bird have not been properly separated.  The underside of the cat is also less carefully finished and was originally held up by a support.  This is evident from the oval shaped block measuring 5.5 x 3cm which, containing a dowel hole that remains about half way down the cat’s belly.
